comment.narrative:
Tanzania adopted the AFRO target of measles elimination by the year 2020. To enhance the control of measles and achieve the regional and global measles elimination goals, the Ministry of Health and partners in Tanzania reviewed the status of measles control in the country and incorporated measles elimination strategy into a comprehensive multi-year plan (c-MYP) for 2016 ? 2020. The purpose of the strategic plan was to systematically guide the planning and implementation of measles elimination activities to achieve measles elimination. 
The targets adopted for 2020 were: 
1.	Measles incidence of less than 1 case per million populations; 
2.	Maintaining 95% measles immunization coverage at national level and in all districts;
3.	Attaining 95% coverage in all scheduled measles SIAs and in response to outbreaks; and
4.	Maintaining the targets for the two main surveillance performance indicators
The strategies applied include;
1. Providing a first dose of measles containing vaccine at or shortly after the 9th month of age, ensuring that all children who missed their first dose receive a dose at the earliest possible time irrespective of their age at the time;
2. Providing a second dose of measles vaccine in the routine immunization program at 18 months of age;
3. Strengthening of Measles and Rubella case based surveillance and documentation of progress towards elimination
WHO has supported intensification of routine immunization under PIRI activities which improved uptake of second dose of MR vaccine.
WHO has supported a workshop of National verification Committee to document progress towards Measles elimination. However since 2020, Tanzania faced a big challenge on laboratory confirmation of suspected measles cases and many specimens were not tested timely. This influenced negatively the Measles rubella case based surveillance performance in Tanzania with many cases becoming compatible.
